  "prompt": "How long can white wine last after it has been open?",
  "response": "White wine can generally last **3-5 days** in the refrigerator after opening. Here's a breakdown:\n\n*   **Lighter, Crisp Whites (Sauvignon Blanc, Pinot Grigio):** Tend to lose their flavor more quickly, so aim for **3 days.**\n\n*   **Fuller-Bodied Whites (Chardonnay, Viognier):** May last up to **5 days.**\n\nHere are some tips to maximize the lifespan of your open white wine:\n\n*   **Refrigerate Immediately:** Cold temperatures slow down oxidation.\n\n*   **Reseal Properly:** Use the original cork or a wine stopper to create a tight seal.\n\n*   **Use Inert Gas Wine Preserver:** Products like Private Preserve inject argon gas into the bottle, displacing oxygen.\n\n*   **Store Upright:** This reduces the surface area exposed to oxygen.\n\n**Signs your white wine has gone bad:**\n\n*   **Vinegar Smell:** A strong, vinegary aroma is a telltale sign of oxidation.\n\n*   **Off-Putting Flavors:** Flavors may be sour, bitter, or generally unpleasant.\n\n*   **Loss of Freshness:** The wine loses its vibrant flavors and aromas.\n\n*   **Brownish Tint:** While not always a definite sign, a noticeable browning can indicate oxidation.",
